<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-integral-FTC" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>

  <objectives>
  <ul>
    <li>
      State and apply the First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to compute derivatives of functions defined by integrals.
    </li>
    <li>
      Interpret accumulation functions
      <m>\displaystyle F(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt</m>
      as total accumulated (signed) change from <m>a</m> to <m>x</m> and recognize them as antiderivatives.
    </li>
    <li>
      Use the relationship <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m> to analyze accumulation functions,
      including determining where they are increasing, decreasing, concave up, and concave down.
    </li>
    <li>
      State and apply the Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus to evaluate definite integrals using antiderivatives.
    </li>
  </ul>
  </objectives>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-ftoc-integral-as-antiderivative">
    <title>Introduction to the Integral as an Antiderivative</title>

    <p>
      In the previous section we used a velocity function <m>v(t)</m> to compute the change in position (displacement) over a time interval <m>[a,b]</m>.
      The distance is an integral defined as a limit of Riemann sums, adding up (velocity)<m>\times</m>(time) over many small time increments:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
       \text{displacement}
      \amp = \amp
      s(b)-s(a)\\[0.8em]
      \amp = \amp
      \displaystyle\lim_{\Delta t\to 0} (v(t_1)\Delta t + v(t_2)\Delta t + \cdots + v(t_n)\Delta t) \\ 
      \amp = \amp
      \displaystyle\int_a^b v(t)\,dt
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      If we fix the starting time <m>a</m> and assume <m>s(a)=0</m>, then taking a variable endpoint <m>b=x</m> gives a function
    </p>

    <me>
      s(x) \ =\ \int_a^x v(t)\,dt.
    </me>

    <p>
      Since the rate of change of position is velocity, <m>s'(x)=v(x)</m>.
      The remarkable point is that the integral function
      <m>\displaystyle \int_a^x v(t)\,dt</m> always produces an antiderivative of <m>v</m>,
      even if we cannot find an antiderivative by reversing derivative formulas.
    </p>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="ssec-ftoc-first-ftc">
    <title>The First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-ftc-1">
      <title>First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Let <m>f</m> be continuous on <m>[a,b]</m> and define
        </p>
        <me>
          F(x)\ =\ \int_a^x f(t)\,dt.
        </me>
        <p>
          Then <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m> for <m>x\in(a,b)</m>.
          In particular, <m>F</m> is the unique antiderivative of <m>f</m> satisfying <m>F(a)=0</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <title>Idea of a Proof</title>
    <p>
      We start from the definition of the derivative:
      <me>F'(x)=\lim_{h\to 0}\dfrac{F(x+h)-F(x)}{h}</me>
      Using the splitting rule for integrals,
      <me>\int_a^{x+h} f(t) ~dt =\int_a^x f(t) ~dt +\int_x^{x+h}f(t) ~dt </me> 
      So we have:
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \displaystyle \frac{F(x+h)-F(x)}{h}
      &amp;=&amp;
      \displaystyle \frac{1}{h}\left(\int_a^{x+h} f(t)\,dt-\int_a^x f(t)\,dt\right)
      \\[0.8em]
      &amp;=&amp;
      \displaystyle \frac{1}{h}\left(\int_a^x f(t) ~dt +\int_x^{x+h}f(t) ~dt -\int_a^x f(t)\,dt\right)
      \\[0.8em]
      &amp;=&amp;
      \displaystyle \frac{1}{h}\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt.
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>Here is a sketch of the graph of <m>f</m> to illustrate the idea:</p>

      <image width="90%">
  <shortdescription>
    Graph of a continuous function f with a small interval [x, x+h] highlighted. 
    The area under the curve of f from x to x+h is shaded in blue, 
    representing the integral \int_x^{x+h} f(t) dt. 
    As h approaches 0, this area approximates a rectangle with height f(x) and width h, 
    leading to the conclusion that the limit of (1/h) times this area equals f(x).
  </shortdescription>
    <latex-image><![CDATA[
\begin{tikzpicture}[xscale=2]
	\fill[blue!20] plot[domain=2:2.4, smooth] (\x, {1+.4*(\x)^2}) -- (2.4,0)--(2,0) -- cycle;
	\draw[->, thick] (-1.3,0) -- (3.3,0) node [right] {$t$};
	\draw[->, thick] (0,-.3) -- (0,5.3);
	%\draw[thin] (0,0) grid (5,5);
	\draw (-.7,1.7) node {$f(t)$};
	\begin{scope}
		\clip (-3.3,0) rectangle (5.3,5.3); 
		\draw[very thick] plot[domain=-1:3, smooth] (\x, {1+.4*(\x)^2});
		\draw[dashed] (2,4) node {\textbar}  -- (2.4,4) node {\textbar} node[pos=.5, above] {$h$};
		\draw (2,0) -- (2, {1+.4*4}) node [pos=.5, left] {$f(x)$} -- (2.4, {1+.4*4}) -- (2.4,0);
	\end{scope}
	\draw (2,2pt)--(2,-2pt) node[below] {$x$};
	\draw (2.4,2pt)--(2.4,-2pt) node[below, font=\small] {$x+h$};
	\begin{scope}
		\clip (2,0) rectangle (2.4, {1+.4*4});
		\foreach \a in {2, 2.08, ..., 4.4} 
		\draw[blue] plot[domain=2:2.4, smooth] (\x, {-2*(\x-\a)});
	\end{scope}
\end{tikzpicture}

 ]]>
    </latex-image>
  </image>

  <p>Geometrically, the integral <m>\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt</m> is the area under the curve of <m>f</m> from <m>x</m> to <m>x+h</m> 
    (shaded in blue above). When <m>h</m> is small, this area is approximately a rectangle with width <m>h</m> and height <m>f(x)</m> (the hatched rectangle in the image above).
    So therefore</p>
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \displaystyle \frac{1}{h}\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt
      &amp;\approx&amp;
      \displaystyle \frac{1}{h}\cdot (f(x)\cdot h)
      \ =\
      f(x).
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>As <m>h\to 0</m>, the approximation becomes exact, so <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m>.</p> 

    <p>For those worried that this is not a rigorous proof, please see the "Finer Details of the Proof" below.</p>


      </proof>
      <proof>
        <title>Finer Details of the Proof</title>
  <p>
    In the proof idea, we used the approximation that <m>\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt\approx f(x)\cdot h</m> when <m>h</m> is small. 
    But how do we know that the limit of the approximation is correct? 
  </p> 
  <p> 
    To control the errors, let's take the absolute minimum value <m>N</m> and absolte maximum value <m>M</m> of the continuous function 
    <m>f</m> on the closed interval <m>[x,x+h]</m> (we can do this by the Extreme Value Theorem). To indicate that these values
    depend on <m>h</m>, we write <m>N_h</m> and <m>M_h</m>. Therefore 
    <me> 
      N_h\le f(t)\le M_h, \quad \text{ for  } t\in [x,x+h]</me> 
    So the bounds rules for definite integrals give
    </p>

    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \displaystyle
      N_h\le \amp f(t) \amp \le M_h \\ 
      N_h((x+h)-x) \le \amp \displaystyle\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt \amp \le M_h ((x+h)-x) \\
      N_h(h) \le \amp \displaystyle\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt \amp \le M_h (h) \\
      N_h \le \amp \dfrac{1}{h}\displaystyle\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt \amp \le M_h 
      \end{array}
    </me>

    <p>
      As <m>h\to 0</m>, the interval shrinks to the point <m>x</m>, so by continuity
      <me>\lim_{h\to 0}N_h=\lim_{h\to 0}M_h=f(x)</me>
      By the squeeze theorem,
      <me>\displaystyle \lim_{h\to 0}\frac{1}{h}\int_x^{x+h} f(t)\,dt = \lim_{h\to 0}N_h=\lim_{h\to 0}M_h=f(x)</me>,
      hence <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m>.
    </p>
    <p> 
      The condition <m>F(a)=\int_a^a f(t)\,dt=0</m> and the antiderivative uniqueness theorem give the uniqueness statement.
    </p>
      </proof>

    </theorem>

    <remark>
    <p>
      In physical language: the rate of change of a cumulative effect up to time <m>x</m> is the strength of the effect at time <m>x</m>.
    </p>
    </remark>

    <remark>
    <p>
      The First Fundamental Theorem can be used as a basic derivative rule:
      if <m>f</m> is continuous, then
    </p>

    <me>
      \frac{d}{dx}\left(\int_a^x f(t)\,dt\right) \ =\ f(x).
    </me>

    <p>
      Here <m>a</m> is a constant, <m>x</m> is the input, and <m>t</m> is a dummy variable that only matters inside the integral.
    </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="ex-ftoc-problem2">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Find the derivative of <m>\displaystyle F(x)=\int_{5}^{x}\sin^4(t)\,dt</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          By the First Fundamental Theorem, <m>F'(x)=\sin^4(x)</m>.
        </p>
        <p> Note that we never needed to evaluate the integral or find an explicit formula for <m>F(x)</m>.
         The First Fundamental Theorem allows us to find the derivative without needing an explicit formula for <m>F</m>.
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

  <subsection xml:id="subsec-accumulation-functions">
    <title>Accumulation Functions</title>
    
    <p>
      The First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus tells us that integrals with a variable
      upper limit naturally produce antiderivatives. 
      Because of this, functions of the form
    </p>

    <me>
      F(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt
    </me>

    <p>
      appear frequently in calculus. Such functions are called
      <term>accumulation functions</term> because they measure the
      total accumulated change of the quantity <m>f(t)</m> from
      <m>t=a</m> up to <m>t=x</m>.
    </p>

    <p>
      As we found in our last section, the value of
      <m>\displaystyle F(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt</m>
      represents the <em>signed area</em> between the graph of
      <m>y=f(t)</m> and the <m>t</m>-axis from <m>a</m> to <m>x</m>.
      Areas above the axis contribute positively,
      while areas below the axis contribute negatively.
    </p>

    <p>Let's get some more practice with accumulation functions and their relationship to the original function.</p>

    <example xml:id="ex-accumulation-graph-analysis">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose the graph of <m>g(t)</m> is shown below.
          And let
        <m>
          A(x)=\displaystyle \int_0^x g(t)\,dt.
        </m>
        </p>

        <sidebyside width="90%">
      <figure>
<caption>
  A graph of <m>g(t)</m> on the interval <m>[0,5]</m> shown on a grid with spacing <m>1</m> in both the horizontal and vertical directions. 
  The signed areas between the curve and the <m>t</m>-axis are labeled.
</caption>        
  <image>
<shortdescription>
  Graph of a function g(t) on a grid with unit spacing. The curve passes through the points 
  (1,0), (2,-2), (3,0), and (4,4). The region above the axis from the left endpoint to t=1 has labeled area 
  0.3. The region below the axis from t=1 to t=3 has labeled area -2.5. The region above the axis from 
  t=3 to t=4 has labeled area 2.3. A dashed vertical line at t=4 marks the endpoint of the accumulated area.
</shortdescription>
    <latex-image><![CDATA[
\begin{tikzpicture}[xscale = 2]
	\fill[blue!20] plot[domain=0:1, smooth] (\x, {(\x)*cos(pi/2 * \x r)});
	\fill[red!20] plot[domain=1:3, smooth] (\x, {(\x)*cos(pi/2 * \x r)});
	\fill[green!20] plot[domain=3:4, smooth] (\x, {(\x)*cos(pi/2 * \x r)}) -- (4,0);
	\draw[thin] (0,-3) grid (5,5);
	\draw[->, thick] (-.15,0) -- (5.15,0) node [right] {$t$} ;
	\draw[->, thick] (0,-3) -- (0,5);
	\draw[very thick] plot[domain=0:5, smooth] (\x, {(\x)*cos(pi/2 * \x r)});
	\draw (.5, 1.5) node {Area = 0.3};
	\draw (2, -.6) node {Area = $-2.5$};
	\draw[very thick, dashed] (4,0) -- (4,4);
	\draw (3.53, .4) node {Area = $2.3$};	
	\draw[->] (0.5,1.2) -- (0.5, 0.6); 
	\draw (3.7,4.4) node {$g(t)$};
\end{tikzpicture}
 ]]>
    </latex-image>
  </image>
        </figure>
       </sidebyside>


        <p>
          Use the graph to answer the following questions.
        </p>

        <p>(a) Find <m>A(4) - A(3)</m>.</p>
        <p>(b) Find <m>A'(2)</m>.</p>
        <p>(c) On which intervals is <m>A(x)</m> increasing?</p>
        <p>(d) On which intervals is <m>A(x)</m> decreasing?</p>
        <p>(e) Where does <m>A(x)</m> have a local maximum?</p>
      </statement>

      <solution>
          <p> (a) By the definition of <m>A</m>, we have
          <me>A(4)-A(3) = \int_0^4 g(t)\,dt - \int_0^3 g(t)\,dt = \int_3^4 g(t)\,dt.</me>
          The integral from 3 to 4 is the area of the green shaded region, which is 2.3.
          So <m>A(4)-A(3)=2.3</m>.
          </p>
          <p> (b) By the First Fundamental Theorem, <m>A'(2)=g(2)</m>.
          From the graph, <m>g(2)=-2</m>, so <m>A'(2)=-2</m>.
          </p>
          <p> (c) The function <m>A(x)</m> is increasing where <m>A'(x)=g(x)\gt 0</m>.
          From the graph, this happens on the intervals <m>(0,1)</m> and <m>(3,5)</m>.
          </p>
          <p> (d) The function <m>A(x)</m> is decreasing where <m>A'(x)=g(x)\lt 0</m>.
          From the graph, this happens on the interval <m>(1,3)</m>.
          </p>
          <p> (e) Local maxima of <m>A(x)</m> occur where <m>A'(x)=g(x)</m> changes from positive to negative.
          From the graph, this happens at <m>x=1</m>, so <m>A(x)</m> has a local maximum at <m>x=1</m>. We 
          can also check the endpoints. Since <m>g(x)\gt 0</m> for <m>x\in(0,1)</m>, <m>A(x)</m> is increasing on <m>(0,1)</m>,

          so <m>x=0</m> is a local minimum. Since <m>g(x)\gt 0</m> for <m>x\in(3,5)</m>, <m>A(x)</m> is increasing on <m>(3,5)</m>, 
          so <m>x=5</m> is a local maximum.
           Therefore the local maxima of <m>A(x)</m> are at <m>x=1</m> and <m>x=5</m>.
          </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

<p>Thanks to the First Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, we can also do curve sketching style problems with accumulation functions.
</p>

<example xml:id="ex-accumulation-curve-sketching"> 
  <statement>
    <p>
      Consider the function <m>H(x)=\displaystyle\int_0^x (1-t)e^t \,dt</m>. 
    </p>
    <p> (a) Evaluate <m>H(0)</m>.</p>
    <p> (b) Find where <m>H(x)</m> is increasing and where it is decreasing.</p>
    <p> (c) Find where <m>H(x)</m> is concave up and where it is concave down.</p>
    <p> (d) Use the information from parts (a)-(c) to find a rough sketch the graph of <m>y=H(x)</m>.</p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p>
      <alert>Part (a):</alert></p>
      <p> <m>H(0)=\int_0^0 (1-t)e^t\,dt=0</m> Since the lower and upper bound of the integral are the same.
    </p>
    <p>
      <alert>Part (b):</alert></p>
      <p> By the First Fundamental Theorem, <me>H'(x)=(1-x)e^x</me>
      Since <m>e^x\gt 0</m> for all <m>x</m>, the sign of <m>H'(x)</m> is determined by the sign of <m>1-x</m>.
      So <m>H'(x)\gt 0</m> when <m>x\lt 1</m>, and <m>H'(x)\lt 0</m> when <m>x\gt 1</m>. </p><p>
      Therefore <m>H(x)</m> is increasing on <m>(-\infty,1)</m> and decreasing on <m>(1,\infty)</m>.
    </p>
    <p> <alert> Part (c)</alert></p> <p>
     To find where <m>H</m> is concave up or down, we need to find the second derivative. 
      We have <me>H''(x)=((1-x)e^x)' = -e^x+(1-x)e^x=-xe^x</me>
      Since <m>e^x\gt 0</m> for all <m>x</m>, the sign of <m>H''(x)</m> is determined by the sign of <m>-x</m>. </p>
      <p>
      So <m>H''(x)\gt 0</m> when <m>x\lt 0</m>, and <m>H''(x)\lt 0</m> when <m>x\gt 0</m>.
      Therefore <m>H(x)</m> is concave up on <m>(-\infty,0)</m> and concave down on <m>(0,\infty)</m>.
    </p>
    <p> <alert>Part (d)</alert></p><p>
    We have the following information about the graph of <m>y=H(x)</m>:
      <ul>
        <li> <m>H(0)=0</m>, so the graph passes through the origin.</li>
        <li> <m>H(x)</m> is increasing on <m>(-\infty,1)</m> and decreasing on <m>(1,\infty)</m>, so the graph has a local maximum at <m>x=1</m>.</li>
        <li> <m>H(x)</m> is concave up on <m>(-\infty,0)</m> and concave down on <m>(0,\infty)</m>, so the graph has an inflection point at <m>x=0</m>.</li>
      </ul>
      Putting this all together, we get the following sketch of the graph of <m>y=H(x)</m>.

        <image width="90%" source="images/curveSketch11.png">
<shortdescription>
  Graph of the accumulation function H(x). 
  The graph passes through the origin, has a local maximum at x=1, 
  and an inflection point at x=0. 
  The graph is increasing and concave up for x less than 0, increasing and concave down for x between 0 and 1, 
  and decreasing and concave down for x larger than 1.
</shortdescription>
        </image>


</p>

  </solution>
</example> 



<p>Now let's move on to the second part of the Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, which allows us to evaluate definite 
  integrals from an antiderivative (instead of having to take a limit of a Riemann sum).</p>


  </subsection>



  <subsection xml:id="ssec-ftoc-second-ftc">
    <title>The Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>

    <theorem xml:id="thm-ftc-2">
      <title>Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus</title>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Suppose <m>F</m> is an antiderivative of a continuous function <m>f</m> on <m>[a,b]</m>, so <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m>.
          Then
        </p>
        <me>
          \int_a^b f(x)\,dx \ =\ F(b)-F(a).
        </me>
        <p>
          That is, the integral of a rate of change is the total change.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <proof>
        <p>
          By the First Fundamental Theorem, <m>I(x)=\int_a^x f(t)\,dt</m> is an antiderivative of <m>f</m>.
          Any two antiderivatives differ by a constant, so <m>I(x)=F(x)+C</m>.
          Since <m>I(a)=0</m>, we get <m>0=F(a)+C</m>, so <m>C=-F(a)</m>.
          Thus <m>I(x)=F(x)-F(a)</m>, and evaluating at <m>x=b</m> gives
          <me>\int_a^b f(x)\,dx=I(b)=F(b)-F(a)</me>
        </p>
      </proof>
    </theorem>



    <example xml:id="ex-ftc-evaluate-integral">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Evaluate <m>\displaystyle \int_{0}^{2} \left(5+x^2-e^{\tfrac12 x}\right)\,dx</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          An antiderivative is <m>F(x)=5x+\frac{1}{3}x^3-2e^{\tfrac12 x}</m>.
          Apply the Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus:
        </p>

        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
          \displaystyle \int_{0}^{2} (5+x^2-2e^{\tfrac12 x})\,dx
          &amp;=&amp;
          F(2)-F(0)
          \\[0.6em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          \left(10+\frac{8}{3}-2e\right)-\left(0-0-2\right)
          \\[0.6em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          12+\frac{8}{3}-2e.
          \end{array}
        </me>

        <remark>
          <p> 
          Another antiderivative is <m>F(x)=5x+\frac{1}{3}x^3-2e^{\tfrac12 x}+7</m>. See that you get the same answer 
          if you use this antiderivative instead:
          </p> 
          <me>
            \begin{array}{rcl}
            \displaystyle \int_{0}^{2} (5+x^2-e^{\tfrac12 x})\,dx
            &amp;=&amp;
            F(2)-F(0)
            \\[0.6em]
            &amp;=&amp;
            \left(10+\frac{8}{3}-2e + 7 \right)-\left(0-0-2 +7\right)
            \\[0.6em]
            &amp;=&amp;
            12+\frac{8}{3}-2e.
            \end{array}
          </me>
          <p>No matter the value of the constant, the difference <m>F(b)-F(a)</m> will always be the same, 
            so we get the same answer for the integral.</p>
        </remark>


      </solution>
    </example>

    <remark xml:id="remark-ftc-evaluation-notation">
       
      <p>
        The Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus allows us to evaluate a definite integral by finding an antiderivative.
        In practice, we often write the evaluation of the integral as
      </p>

      <me>
        \int_a^b f(x)\,dx \ =\ F(b)-F(a) \ =\ \left. F(x)\right|_a^b.
      </me>

      <p>
        The notation <m>\left. F(x)\right|_a^b</m> is read as "F of x evaluated from a to b" and means <m>F(b)-F(a)</m>.
        This is just a convenient shorthand for writing the difference of the antiderivative at the endpoints.
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example xml:id="ex-ftc-area-evaluate">
      <statement>
        <p>
          Determine the net area between <m>y=\dfrac{1+\sqrt{x}}{x}</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis on the interval <m>[1,4]</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The net area is given by a definite integral
        </p>
        <me>
          \begin{array}{rcl}
          \text{net area} &amp;=&amp;
          \displaystyle \int_1^4 \frac{1+\sqrt{x}}{x}\,dx \\[0.6em] 
          &amp;=&amp;
          \displaystyle \int_1^4 \frac{1}{x} + \frac{1}{\sqrt{x}}\,dx
          \\[0.6em]
          &amp;=&amp;
          \left. \ln|x|+2\sqrt{x}\right|_1^4   \\[0.6em] 
          &amp;=&amp;
          \left(\ln(4)+4\right)-\left(\ln(1)+2\right) \\[0.6em] 
          &amp;=&amp;
          \ln(4)+2       
          \end{array}
        </me>
        <p> So the net area is <m>\ln(4)+2</m>.</p> 
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>

<subsection xml:id="additional-worked-problems-integral-FTC">
  <title>Additional Worked-Out Examples</title>

  <p>
    To keep this section at a reasonable length, we include only a few representative examples directly in the text.
    If you find yourself stuck on a homework problem, or if you are studying before a quiz or exam, additional
    fully worked-out examples are available via: 
    <alert>
      <xref ref="subsec-integral-FTC">
        Additional Worked-Out Problems for The Fundamental Theorem of Calculus
      </xref>
    </alert>
  </p>

</subsection>


  <exercises xml:id="exercises-ftoc">
    <title>Practice / Study Problems</title>


  <exercisegroup>
    <title>Some True/False Problems</title>

    <introduction>
      <p>
        Determine whether each statement is true or false and briefly justify your reasoning.
      </p>
    </introduction>


<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-1">
  <statement>
    <p>
      The notation <m>\left. F(x)\right|_a^b</m> means <m>F(a)-F(b)</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>False.</alert> The notation <m>\left. F(x)\right|_a^b</m> means <m>F(b)-F(a)</m>.</p>
  </solution>
</exercise>


<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-2">
  <statement>
    <p>
      <m>\displaystyle\int_0^{\pi/4} \sec^2(x)~dx = 1</m>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>True.</alert> An antiderivative of <m>\sec^2(x)</m> is <m>\tan(x)</m>, so evaluating from <m>0</m> to <m>\pi/4</m> gives <m>\tan(\pi/4)-\tan(0)=1-0=1</m>.</p>
  </solution>

</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-3" >
  <statement>
    <p>
      <m>\displaystyle\int_1^{e} \dfrac{1}{x}~dx  \lt \displaystyle\int_0^{1} \dfrac{1}{1+x^2} ~dx </m>
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>False.</alert>
      Using the Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, we can evaluate both integrals. 
      The left integral evaluates to 
    </p> 
    <me>
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \displaystyle\int_1^{e} \frac{1}{x}~dx
      &amp;=&amp;
       \ln|x|\Bigg|_1^e
      \\[0.6em]
      &amp;=&amp;       \ln(e)-\ln(1) = 1-0 = 1
\end{array}
    </me>
    <p>The right integral evaluates to </p> 
    <me> 
      \begin{array}{rcl}
      \displaystyle\int_0^{1} \dfrac{1}{1+x^2} ~dx
      &amp;=&amp;
      \left. \arctan(x)\right|_0^1 
      \\[0.6em]
      &amp;=&amp; \arctan(1)-\arctan(0)
      \\[0.6em]
      &amp;=&amp; \frac{\pi}{4}-0 = \frac{\pi}{4}
      \end{array}
    </me>
    <p> 
      Since we know <m>\pi\lt 4</m> we have <m>\frac{\pi}{4}\lt 1</m>, so <m>\displaystyle\int_1^{e} \dfrac{1}{x}~dx \gt \displaystyle\int_0^{1} \dfrac{1}{1+x^2} ~dx </m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>


<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-4">
  <statement>
    <p> The area between <m>y=5^x</m> and the <m>x</m>-axis on the interval <m>[0,1]</m> is <m>5</m>.</p>
    </statement>
    <solution>
      <p>
        <alert>False.</alert> The area is given by the integral <m>\displaystyle\int_0^1 5^x\,dx</m>.
        An antiderivative of <m>5^x</m> is <m>\frac{5^x}{\ln(5)}</m>, so evaluating from 0 to 1 gives
        <me>
  \begin{array}{rcl}
  \displaystyle\int_0^1 5^x\,dx
  &amp;=&amp;
  \left. \frac{5^x}{\ln(5)}\right|_0^1
  \\[0.6em]
  &amp;=&amp;
  \frac{5}{\ln(5)}-\frac{1}{\ln(5)} 
  \\[0.6em]
  &amp;=&amp;
  \frac{4}{\ln(5)}
  \end{array}
        </me>
        Which is certainly not the same as 5.
      </p>
    </solution>
</exercise>




<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-5">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>F(x)=\displaystyle\int_2^x e^{t-2}\,dt</m>, then <m>F(2)=1</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>False.</alert> Since the lower and upper limits are the same, <m>F(2)=\displaystyle\int_2^2 e^{t-2}\,dt=0</m>.</p>
  </solution>
</exercise>
    



<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-6">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m>, then <m>\displaystyle\int_a^b f(x)\,dx</m> represents the total change in <m>F</m> from <m>x=a</m> to <m>x=b</m>.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>True.</alert> By the Second Fundamental Theorem of Calculus, <m>\displaystyle\int_a^b f(x)\,dx=F(b)-F(a)</m>.</p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-7">
  <statement>
    <p>
      Water flows into a tank at a rate of <m>r(t)=1+\sqrt{t}</m> liters per minute, where <m>t</m> is the time in minutes. 
      The total amount of water that flows into the tank in the first 9 minutes is 27 liters.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>True.</alert> The integral <m>\displaystyle\int_0^9 r(t)\,dt</m> gives the total amount of water that flows into 
      the tank from time <m>t=0</m> to time <m>t=9</m> minutes. Evaluate</p>
      <me> 
        \begin{array}{rcl}
        \displaystyle\int_0^9 (1+\sqrt{t})\,dt
        &amp;=&amp;
        \displaystyle\int_0^9 1 + t^{1/2}\,dt
        \\[0.6em]
        &amp;=&amp;
        \left. t+\frac{2}{3}t^{3/2}\right|_0^9
        \\[0.6em]
        &amp;=&amp;
        (9+\frac{2}{3}\cdot 27) - (0+0)
        \\[0.6em]
        &amp;=&amp;
        27
        \end{array}
      </me> <p> 
      So the total amount of water that flows into the tank in the first 9 minutes is 27 liters.
  </p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-8">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>F(x)=\displaystyle\int_0^x f(t)\,dt</m> and <m>f(x)&gt;0</m> on an interval, then <m>F(x)</m> is increasing on that interval.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>True.</alert> Since <m>F'(x)=f(x)</m>, if <m>f(x)&gt;0</m>, then <m>F</m> is increasing.</p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-9">
  <statement>
    <p>
      If <m>F(x)=\displaystyle\int_0^x f(t)\,dt</m> and <m>F(x)&gt;0</m> on an interval, then <m>f(x)</m> is increasing on that interval.
    </p>
  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>False.</alert> The condition <m>F(x)&gt;0</m> does not imply that <m>f(x)</m> is increasing. 
      For example, consider <m>F(x)=1+\tfrac13 x^3</m> on <m>(-1,0)</m>. Then <m>F(x) &gt;0</m>, and yet <m>f(x) = x^2</m> is decreasing 
      on <m>(-1,0)</m></p>
  </solution>
</exercise>

<exercise xml:id="ex-ftc-true-false-10">
  <statement>
    <p>Consider the graph of <m>f(t)</m> below and let <m>F(x)=\displaystyle\int_0^x f(t)\,dt</m>.</p>
    <sidebyside width="80%">
  <image>
  <shortdescription>
  Graph of a function f(t). The curve starts of positive from t=0 to t=3 and the graph has a 
  labeled area of 5. The curve then goes negative from t=3 to t=8 and has a labeled area of -12. 
  The graph passes through the points (0,0), (3,0), and (8,0).
  </shortdescription>
    <latex-image><![CDATA[
\begin{tikzpicture}
	\draw[fill=green!20] plot[domain=0:3, smooth] (\x, {.1*(\x)*(\x-3)*(\x-8)});
	\draw[fill=red!20] plot[domain=3:8, smooth] (\x, {.1*(\x)*(\x-3)*(\x-8)});
	\draw[->, thick] (-.3,0) -- (8.3,0) node [right] {$t$} ;
	\draw[->, thick] (0,-4) -- (0,3);
	\draw[very thick] plot[domain=0:8, smooth] (\x, {.1*(\x)*(\x-3)*(\x-8)});
	\draw (1.3, .6) node {Area = 5};
	\draw (5.7, -1.3) node {Area = $-12$};	
	\draw (2.5,1.5) node {$f(t)$};
	\foreach \x in {8} {
		\draw (\x, -2pt) -- (\x, 2pt) node[font=\small, above] {\x};	
	} 
	
\end{tikzpicture}

 ]]>
    </latex-image>
  </image>
      </sidebyside>
      <p> Then <m>F'(8) \gt F(8)</m>.</p>

  </statement>
  <solution>
    <p><alert>True.</alert>
    We can evaluate <m>F(8)</m> by finding the signed area under the graph of <m>f(t)</m> from <m>t=0</m> to <m>t=8</m> which is 
    <m>5 + (-12)=-7</m>. Since <m>F'(8)=f(8)=0\gt -7=F(8)</m>, we have <m>F'(8)\gt F(8)</m>.
    </p> 
  </solution>
</exercise>




    </exercisegroup>
  </exercises>

</section>